      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Company Man",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " is something truly shocking in the best possible way. The combat is fast paced and intuitive; the combination of pattern recognition, secondary abilities and difficulty almost makes it feel like a more forgiving ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 2,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "Blasphemous",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "__GHOST_URL__/blasphemous-switch-review/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ". The difficulty curve is nice and feels very much like old-school ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Mega Man",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " in how it’s constructed; you fight through a self-contained area that ends with a boss fight and then move on to the next self-contained area with another boss fight. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The level design is vibrant and varied, each one with different enemies, puzzle mechanics and colour schemes. This game could’ve easily fallen into a grayscale aesthetic but instead, it subverts that trope with vibrant colours alongside the air of deathly monotony. The amount of variety in this game that is so clearly themed around the boring repetition of a 9-5 work cycle is a really interesting and effective choice that keeps it from ever feeling repetitive or boring. The boss fights, level design, combat, puzzles and pretty much everything else are constantly keeping the player on their toes in intelligent and dynamic ways.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "html",
        "html": "<a href=\"https://powera.pxf.io/c/3324894/1258631/15385\" target=\"_top\" id=\"1258631\"><img src=\"//a.impactradius-go.com/display-ad/15385-1258631\" border=\"0\" alt=\"\" width=\"728\" height=\"90\"/></a><img height=\"0\" width=\"0\" src=\"https://imp.pxf.io/i/3324894/1258631/15385\" style=\"position:absolute;visibility:hidden;\" border=\"0\" />"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The writing is a biting satire of capitalism and corporate culture that is so funny, it hurts. It’s an unapologetic view of the workplace that is both profound and cartoonish. The first area you encounter looks like something out of an episode of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Adventure Time",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", with a blatant ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Inferno",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "-parody storyline: hellish and kind of off putting but visually amazing. The visual storytelling is very efficient and works in conjunction with the dialogue/quips delivered directly to the camera in order to create something that makes the player laugh and then reflect about their professional life. The dialogue feels like an episode of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Office",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " insomuch as it’s very ordinary but doles out quick quips with a wink that keeps the player engaged, even though there’s not much actual plot. It’s smart and self-aware in a way that actually benefits from its simplicity.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
